==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ham
<hw>Ham</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>ham</ets>;
akin to D. <ets>ham</ets>, dial. G. <ets>hamme</ets>, OHG.
<ets>hamma</ets>. Perh. named from the bend at the ham, and akin to E.
<ets>chamber</ets>. Cf. <er>Gammon</er> ham.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The region back of the knee
joint; the popliteal space; the hock.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The thigh of any animal; especially, the thigh of a
hog cured by salting and smoking.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A plentiful lack of wit, together with most weak
<qex>hams</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ham</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Ham
<hw>Ham</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <ety>[Short
for <er>hamfatter</er>.]</ety> <def>a person who performs in a showy or
exaggerated style; -- used especially of actors. Also used
attributively, <as>as, a <ex>ham</ex> actor</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The licensed operator of an amateur radio
station.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ham</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Ham
<hw>Ham</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧m)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <fld>(Theater)</fld>
<def>To act with exaggerated voice and gestures; to overact.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>ham it up</b></col> <cd>to act in a showy fashion or to
act so as to attract attention; to ham.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hamadryad</ent>⟦br⟧
